Anterior legs laterigrade and superposed (leg I laying over leg II when spider in resting position, Fig. 1 ); leg III anteriorly oriented and leg IV posteriorly oriented. Anterior legs distinctively larger and stouter than the posterior ones. Femora I and II armed with two rows of ventral conical tubercles (FeT, Figs 2 E, 7E), patellae I and II elongated. Tibiae and metatarsi I and II round in cross-section, armed with short, slightly curved macrosetae, with rounded base and acute edge (sometimes bifid, Fig. 3 E). Metatarsi III and IV round in cross-section with distinct setae tuff on the distal third. Anterior tibiae with a concave area on the dorso-retrolateral face ( Fig. 6 B), where a sensorial pit can be found (SPt, Figs 6 C, D) in the proximal part. The same region contains both duster-shaped setae ( Fig. 6 E) and trichobothria ( Figs 6 C, D). Tarsi I and II of similar size as metatarsi, wider near joint to metatarsi. Tarsi III and IV small and rounded in cross-section, forming an acute angle with the metatarsi, with a dense field of setae along its extension. Leg formula I-II-IV-III. Palp with spatulated setae and a tarsal claw. Epigynum with a discrete, colorless incomplete median septum and lowered median area (better seen on SEM, Figs 15 B, E, H). Epigynal plate at the same level as the opisthosoma (
E. heterogaster
,
E. rubripes
) or slightly elevated (
E. planus
). Copulatory openings sclerotized ( Figs 3 A, 8A, 12A); vestibular edges sclerotized, forming a smooth and rounded atrium ( Figs 15 B, E, H). Copulatory ducts long, S-shaped ( Fig. 3 C) with upper (anterior) curve (CV) enlarged, similar to a secondary spermatheca (see Bonaldo 2000 ;
Machado et al. 2015
) at the distal part ( Figs 15 A, D, G) and getting narrower near the copulatory openings and distant from the spermatheca. Spermathecae rounded or bean-shaped. Fertilization ducts long and thin, oriented dorsally near the spermatheca and turning retrolaterally ( Figs 3 C–D, 8B–C, 12B).
